### 1. **Input Validation and Sanitization**

#### **Validation**
Ensure that the input meets certain criteria before processing it. This includes checking the length, format, and type of the input.

#### **Sanitization**
Remove or escape potentially harmful characters to prevent injection attacks.

#### **Example Code in PHP:**

```php
function validateAndSanitizeInput($input) {
    // Trim whitespace
    $input = trim($input);

    // Check for empty input
    if (empty($input)) {
        return null;
    }

    // Escape special characters to prevent SQL injection
    $sanitizedInput = mysqli_real_escape_string($conn, $input);

    // Additional validation (e.g., length, format)
    if (strlen($sanitizedInput) > 255) {
        return null;
    }

    return $sanitizedInput;
}

// Usage example
$userInput = $_POST['username'];
$safeUsername = validateAndSanitizeInput($userInput);

if ($safeUsername === null) {
    die("Invalid input");
}
```

### 2. **Parameterized Queries (Prepared Statements)**

Using parameterized queries or prepared statements is a robust way to prevent SQL injection.

#### **Example Code in PHP with MySQLi:**

```php
function executeQuery($query, $params) {
    global $conn;

    // Prepare the statement
    $stmt = $conn->prepare($query);

    // Bind parameters
    $types = '';
    foreach ($params as $param) {
        if (is_int($param)) {
            $types .= 'i';
        } elseif (is_string($param)) {
            $types .= 's';
        } else {
            throw new Exception("Unsupported parameter type");
        }
    }
    $stmt->bind_param($types, ...$params);

    // Execute the statement
    $stmt->execute();
    $stmt->close();
}

// Usage example
$username = $_POST['username'];
$password = $_POST['password'];

// Prepare the query
$query = "INSERT INTO users (username, password) VALUES (?, ?)";
$params = [$username, $password];

executeQuery($query, $params);
```

### 3. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**

CSP helps mitigate XSS attacks by defining a policy that browsers enforce.

#### **Example CSP Header:**

```http
Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' https://trusted-cdn.com; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; img-src 'self' data:; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'self' https://api.example.com; frame-src 'none'; object-src 'none'; media-src 'self'; form-action 'self'; base-uri 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none';
```

#### **Example Code in PHP to Set CSP Header:**

```php
header("Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' https://trusted-cdn.com; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; img-src 'self' data:; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'self' https://api.example.com; frame-src 'none'; object-src 'none'; media-src 'self'; form-action 'self'; base-uri 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'");
```

### 4. **Anti-CSRF Tokens**

Anti-CSRF tokens help prevent Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks by ensuring that requests come from a trusted source.

#### **Example Code in PHP:**

```php
function generateCsrfToken() {
    $token = bin2hex(random_bytes(32));
    $_SESSION['csrf_token'] = $token;
    return $token;
}

function validateCsrfToken($token) {
    if (!isset($_SESSION['csrf_token']) || $_SESSION['csrf_token'] !== $token) {
        die("Invalid CSRF token");
    }
}

// Usage example
$csrfToken = generateCsrfToken();

// In the form
<form method="post">
    <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="<?php echo htmlspecialchars($csrfToken); ?>">
    <!-- Other form fields -->
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

// On the server-side
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $csrfToken = $_POST['csrf_token'];
    validateCsrfToken($csrfToken);
    // Process the form
}
```

### 5. **Secure Storage of Sensitive Data**

Ensure that sensitive data such as passwords are stored securely using strong hashing algorithms.

#### **Example Code in PHP:**

```php
function hashPassword($password) {
    return password_hash($password, PASSWORD_BCRYPT);
}

function verifyPassword($password, $hashedPassword) {
    return password_verify($password, $hashedPassword);
}

// Usage example
$password = $_POST['password'];
$hashedPassword = hashPassword($password);

// Store $hashedPassword in the database

// Verification
if (verifyPassword($password, $hashedPassword)) {
    // Password matches
} else {
    // Password does not match
}
```

### 6. **Error Handling and Logging**

Provide generic error messages to avoid exposing sensitive information.

#### **Example Code in PHP:**

```php
try {
    // Your code here
} catch (Exception $e) {
    // Log the error
    error_log($e->getMessage());

    // Return a generic error message
    http_response_code(500);
    echo "An unexpected error occurred. Please try again later.";
}
```

